<!--
    Indonesian (id) — translated from values-de/ (German source of truth).

    Script notes:
    • Indonesian uses the Latin alphabet with no diacritics beyond common
      loanword spellings; very low rendering complexity.
    • The same strings.xml serves both Indonesian (id) and Malay (ms) users
      as the two languages are mutually intelligible and Android falls back
      from ms → id when no values-ms/ directory exists.  A separate values-ms/
      with minor lexical adjustments can be added later if needed.
    • Register: formal/polite (Anda, tidak, dll.) as is standard for
      Indonesian app UIs.
    • "Binge drinking" → minum berlebihan (public-health term in Indonesian).
    • DHS is kept as "DHS"; WHO as "WHO" (both used in Indonesian public health).
    • day_change_time_value: Indonesian omits a clock-suffix word; HH:MM alone.
    • Decimal separator in Indonesian is a comma (,), but numeric format strings
      (%1$s, %1$d) are passed pre-formatted by the app, so no change needed here.
-->
